Here's an example of generating a sine wave using AudioStreamGenerator in Godot with C#:

```csharp
[Export] public AudioStreamPlayer Player { get; set; }

private AudioStreamGeneratorPlayback _playback; // Holds the AudioStreamGeneratorPlayback.
private float _sampleHz;
private float _pulseHz = 440.0f; // Frequency of the sound wave.

public override void _Ready()
{
    if (Player.Stream is AudioStreamGenerator generator) // Cast to access MixRate.
    {
        _sampleHz = generator.MixRate; // Obtain sample rate.
        Player.Play();  // Start playback.
        _playback = (AudioStreamGeneratorPlayback)Player.GetStreamPlayback();
        FillBuffer();  // Fill the buffer with audio data.
    }
}

public void FillBuffer()
{
    double phase = 0.0;
    float increment = _pulseHz / _sampleHz; // Determine increment based on pulse frequency and sampling rate.
    int framesAvailable = _playback.GetFramesAvailable();  // Get number of frames available to fill.

    for (int i = 0; i < framesAvailable; i++)
    {
        _playback.PushFrame(Vector2.One * (float)Mathf.Sin(phase * Mathf.Tau));  // Generate audio data.
        phase = Mathf.PosMod(phase + increment, 1.0); // Increment phase, wrap using PosMod.
    }
}
```

### Important Note:
- The audio stream should be set to an AudioStreamGenerator in the AudioStreamPlayer node for this to work.
- While this example is implemented in C#, note that using AudioStreamGenerator in GDScript is possible but may require adjusted configurations due to performance limitations. Consider a lower mix_rate (e.g., 11,025 Hz or 22,050 Hz) to improve performance.

Here's a simple C# class to manage audio generation with AudioStreamGenerator in Godot:

```csharp
public class AudioGeneratorManager
{
    [Export] public AudioStreamPlayer Player { get; set; }

    private AudioStreamGeneratorPlayback _playback;
    private float _sampleHz;
    private float _pulseHz;

    public void Initialize(float pulseFrequency)
    {
        _pulseHz = pulseFrequency; // Set the sine wave frequency.
        if (Player.Stream is AudioStreamGenerator generator)
        {
            _sampleHz = generator.MixRate; // Get the mix rate from the generator.
            Player.Play(); // Start the audio playback.
            _playback = (AudioStreamGeneratorPlayback)Player.GetStreamPlayback();
        }
        else
        {
            GD.PushError("Player must have an AudioStreamGenerator as its stream!");
        }
    }

    public void FillBuffer()
    {
        if (_playback == null)
        {
            GD.PushWarning("Playback is not initialized!");
            return;
        }

        double phase = 0.0;
        float increment = _pulseHz / _sampleHz;
        int framesAvailable = _playback.GetFramesAvailable();

        for (int i = 0; i < framesAvailable; i++)
        {
            _playback.PushFrame(Vector2.One * (float)Mathf.Sin(phase * Mathf.Tau));
            phase = Mathf.PosMod(phase + increment, 1.0);
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage Notes:
- Initialize the class with a frequency via the `Initialize` method, and ensure the AudioPlayer is configured correctly.
- Call `FillBuffer()` regularly (e.g., in the 
 `_Process` method) to keep audio generated and pushed to the player.
- Includes basic error handling to alert if the player is not set up correctly or if the playback hasn't been initialized properly.

