Here's a C# example to store and read a signed integer as 16 bits in Godot, with proper overflow handling:

```csharp
using Godot;
using System;

public class FileHandler : Node
{
    const short MAX_15B = (short)(1 << 15);
    const short MAX_16B = (short)(1 << 16);

    public static short Unsigned16ToSigned(ushort unsigned)
    {
        return (short)((unsigned + MAX_15B) % MAX_16B - MAX_15B);
    }

    public override void _Ready()
    {
        FileAccess f = FileAccess.Open("user://file.dat", FileAccess.ModeFlags.ReadWrite);
        f.Store16((ushort)-42); // This wraps around to 65494
        f.Store16(121); // In bounds, will store 121
        f.Seek(0); // Go back to start to read stored values.

        ushort read1 = f.Get16(); // Should read 65494
        ushort read2 = f.Get16(); // Should read 121
        short converted1 = Unsigned16ToSigned(read1); // -42
        short converted2 = Unsigned16ToSigned(read2); // 121
    }
}
```

In this C# example, the method ensures that any out-of-bound value is wrapped into a valid 16-bit unsigned representation, and provides a conversion back to the signed format when reading.

