Here's a C# method to safely store a signed 16-bit integer. It checks if the value is within the acceptable range before storage:

```csharp
public void StoreSigned16(FileAccess f, int value)
{
    if (value < -32768 || value > 32767)
    {
        throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException("value", "The value must be in the range [-2^15, 2^15 - 1].");
    }
    // Cast the value to short and store it
    f.Store16((ushort)(value & 0xFFFF)); // Masking ensures value fits
}

public override void _Ready()
{
    using var f = FileAccess.Open("user://file.dat", FileAccess.ModeFlags.WriteRead);

    // Valid value within range
    StoreSigned16(f, 100); // Will store 100
    StoreSigned16(f, -100); // Will store -100 as unsigned representation

    // Trying to store an out-of-range value will throw exception
    try
    {
        StoreSigned16(f, 40000); // Should throw an exception
    }
    catch (ArgumentOutOfRangeException e)
    {
        GD.Print(e.Message); // Prints error message
    }

    f.Seek(0);
    ushort readValue = f.Get16(); // Read back the value
    short signedValue = (short)readValue; // Convert to signed int
    GD.Print(signedValue); // Prints stored value and respects sign
}
```

This example gives a safe method to store signed integers as 16-bit values while illustrating error handling.

