Here's a more complex implementation in C# to handle and log multiple input events asynchronously:

```csharp
private Queue<InputEventKey> _inputQueue = new Queue<InputEventKey>();

public override void _Input(InputEvent @event)
{
    if (@event is InputEventKey inputEventKey)
    {
        GrabInput(inputEventKey);
    }
}

private async void GrabInput(InputEventKey inputEventKey)
{
    // Add the event to a queue
    _inputQueue.Enqueue(inputEventKey);
    await ProcessInputs();
}

private async Task ProcessInputs()
{
    while (_inputQueue.Count > 0)
    {
        var inputEventKey = _inputQueue.Dequeue();
        var keycode = DisplayServer.KeyboardGetKeycodeFromPhysical(inputEventKey.PhysicalKeycode);
        GD.Print(OS.GetKeycodeString(keycode));
        await Task.Yield(); // Yield to allow other processes
    }
}
```

In this code, we use a queue to capture multiple `InputEventKey` events. The `GrabInput` method adds events to the queue and calls `ProcessInputs` asynchronously, which logs each keycode smoothly.

