In C#, signals are represented using delegates and the `[Signal]` attribute. Below is an example:

```csharp
using Godot;
using System;

public class Player : Node
{
    [Signal] public delegate void Attacked();
    [Signal] public delegate void ItemDropped(string itemName, int amount);

    public void Attack()
    {
        EmitSignal("Attacked");  // Emit the Attacked signal
    }

    public void DropItem(string name, int quantity)
    {
        EmitSignal("ItemDropped", name, quantity);  // Emit ItemDropped signal with parameters
    }
}
```

In this example, we define two signals: `Attacked` and `ItemDropped`. The `Attack()` method emits the `Attacked` signal, while the `DropItem()` method emits the `ItemDropped` signal along with its parameters. Signals help in decoupling the methods, allowing for flexible event handling.

