In Godot, when using a TileMap with a TileSetScenesCollectionSource, tiles automatically instantiate associated scenes at the tile's position in the TileMap once it enters the scene tree. If a tile is removed from the TileMap, the associated scene is also freed.

To handle tile removal gracefully in C#, you can override the `_Notification` method to monitor when tiles are deleted:

```csharp
public class MyTileMap : TileMap
{
    public override void _Notification(int what)
    {
        if (what == NotificationReady)
        {
            // Initialization code here.
            foreach (Vector2I position in GetCells())
            {
                FreeSceneForTile(position);
            }
        }
    }

    private void FreeSceneForTile(Vector2I cell)
    {
        int sourceId = GetCellSourceId(cell);
        if (sourceId > -1)
        {
            TileSetSource source = TileSet.GetSource(sourceId);
            if (source is TileSetScenesCollectionSource sceneSource)
            {
                int altId = GetCellAlternativeTile(cell);
                PackedScene scene = sceneSource.GetSceneTileScene(altId);
                // Logic to free the scene if one exists.
                if (scene != null)
                {
                    // Assume there's a method to free the scene instance stored as a child.
                    foreach (Node child in GetChildren())
                    {
                        if (child is InstanceNode && child.PackedScene == scene)
                        {
                            child.QueueFree();
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```
This code structure provides a robust way to manage scene tiles and ensures the associated scenes are freed when their corresponding tiles are removed from the TileMap.

