// Begin a compute list and bind the uniform set
var computeList = rd.ComputeListBegin();
rd.ComputeListBindUniformSet(computeList, uniformSet, 0);
```
This binds the specified uniform set to the compute list for execution.

To execute a compute shader in Godot using csharp, you must submit the pipeline to the GPU and wait for the execution to finish:
```csharp
// Submit to GPU and wait for sync
rd.Submit();
rd.Sync();
```
This ensures that the GPU completes the task before proceeding.

When dispatching compute shaders, be cautious not to read or write to indices outside the range of your buffer. Doing so may lead to issues, including accessing memory outside the shader's control:
```csharp
// Ensure your buffer access is within the correct range
if (index >= 0 && index < buffer.Length)
{
    // Safe access
}
else
{
    GD.Print("Index out of bounds!");
}
```

To retrieve and print results from a compute shader execution, you can read back the data from the buffers like this:
```csharp
// Read back the data from the buffers
var outputBytes = rd.BufferGetData(buffer);
var output = new float[input.Length];
Buffer.BlockCopy(outputBytes, 0, output, 0, outputBytes.Length);
GD.Print("Input: ", string.Join(", ", input));
GD.Print("Output: ", string.Join(", ", output));
```

A TDR, or Timeout Detection and Recovery, can occur if a compute shader takes too long to execute. To minimize the risk of triggering a TDR, consider splitting your compute shader into multiple dispatches:
```csharp
// Example pattern for splitting your compute dispatch
for (int i = 0; i < totalDispatchCount; i++)
{
    rd.DispatchCompute(shader, workGroupX, 1, 1);
    rd.Sync();  // Ensure completed before next dispatch
}
```

