To implement a custom shader for the chroma key effect in Godot, you can start by using the `ChromaKeyShader.gdshader` file with code like the following:
```gdshader
shader_type canvas_item;

uniform vec4 chroma_key_color;
uniform float pickup_range;
uniform float fade_amount;

void fragment() {
    vec4 texColor = texture(TEXTURE, FRAGCOORD.xy / SCREEN_SIZE);
    float distance = length(texColor.rgb - chroma_key_color.rgb);
    if (distance < pickup_range) {
        discard;
    } else {
        float fade = smoothstep(pickup_range, pickup_range + fade_amount, distance);
        texColor.a *= fade;
        COLOR = texColor;
    }
}
```
This shader uses distance calculations to remove the specified chroma key color from the video.

When a pixel’s color is close to the chroma key color, the shader will discard that pixel, effectively making it transparent. This is a part of the shader's logic:
```gdshader
if (distance < pickup_range) {
    discard;
}```
This ensures that the pixels which match the chroma key color are removed from the final output.

